# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: xxe-prevention
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] In computer security, a **billion laughs attack** is a type of denial-of-service attack (DoS attack) which is aimed at parsers of XML documents.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] It is also referred to as an **XML bomb** or as an exponential entity expansion attack.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] The example attack consists of defining 10 entities, each defined as consisting of 10 of the previous entity, with the document consisting of a single instance of the largest entity, which expands to one billion copies of the first entity.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] Versions with larger amount of entries also exist.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] In the most frequently cited example, the first entity is the string "lol", hence the name "billion laughs".
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] At the time this vulnerability was first reported, the computer memory used by a billion instances of the string "lol" would likely exceed that available to the process parsing the XML.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] While the original form of the attack was aimed specifically at XML parsers, the term may be applicable to similar subjects as well.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] The problem was first reported as early as 2002, but began to be widely addressed in 2008.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] Defenses against this kind of attack include capping the memory allocated in an individual parser if loss of the document is acceptable, or treating entities symbolically and expanding them lazily only when (and to the extent) their content is to be used.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] When an XML parser loads this document, it sees that it includes one root element, "lolz", that contains the text "&lol9;".
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] However, "&lol9;" is a defined entity that expands to a string containing ten "&lol8;" strings.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] Each "&lol8;" string is a defined entity that expands to ten "&lol7;" strings, and so on.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] After all the entity expansions have been processed, this small (< 1 KB) block of XML will actually contain 109 = a billion "lol"s, taking up almost 3 gigabytes of memory.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] The billion laughs attack described above can take an exponential amount of space or time.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] The **quadratic blowup** variation causes quadratic growth in resource requirements by simply repeating a large entity over and over again, to avoid countermeasures that detect heavily nested entities.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] This crashed earlier versions of Go because the Go YAML processor (contrary to the YAML spec) expands references as if they were macros.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] The Go YAML processor was modified to fail parsing if the result object becomes too large.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] Enterprise software like Kubernetes has been affected by this attack through its YAML parser.
[src:xxe-prevention/billion-laughs-attack] For this reason, either a parser with intentionally limited capabilities is preferred (like StrictYAML) or file formats that do not allow references are often preferred for data arriving from untrusted sources.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] A **document type definition** (**DTD**) is a specification file that contains a set of *markup declarations* that define a *document type* for an SGML-family markup language (GML, SGML, XML, HTML).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The DTD specification file can be used to validate documents.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] A DTD defines the valid building blocks of an XML document.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] It defines the document structure with a list of validated elements and attributes.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] A DTD can be declared inline inside an XML document, or as an external reference.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] DTDs persist in applications that need special publishing characters, such as the XML and HTML Character Entity References, which derive from larger sets defined as part of the ISO SGML standard effort.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] An attempt to create namespace-aware DTDs was being developed as Part 9 of ISO DSDL, but this was ultimately withdrawn.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] As of 2009, newer XML namespace-aware schema languages (such as W3C XML Schema and ISO RELAX NG) have largely superseded DTDs as a better way to validate XML structure.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] A DTD is associated with an XML or SGML document by means of a document type declaration (DOCTYPE).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The DOCTYPE appears in the syntactic fragment *doctypedecl* near the start of an XML document.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The declaration establishes that the document is an instance of the type defined by the referenced DTD.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The declarations in the internal subset form part of the DOCTYPE in the document itself.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The declarations in the external subset are located in a separate text file.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The external subset may be referenced via a *public identifier* and/or a *system identifier*.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Programs for reading documents may not be required to read the external subset.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] However, such documents are still fully parsable in the *non*-standalone mode of validating parsers, which signals an error if it can not locate these external entities with their specified *public identifier* (FPI) or *system identifier* (a URI), or are inaccessible.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Non-validating parsers *may* eventually attempt to locate these external entities in the *non*-standalone mode (by partially interpreting the DTD only to resolve their declared parsable entities), but do not validate the content model of these documents.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] All HTML 4.01 documents conform to one of three SGML DTDs.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The system identifiers of these DTDs, if present in the DOCTYPE, are URI references.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] A system identifier usually points to a specific set of declarations in a resolvable location.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] SGML allows mapping public identifiers to system identifiers in catalogs that are optionally available to the URI resolvers used by document parsing software.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] This DOCTYPE can only appear *after* the optional XML declaration, and before the document body, if the document syntax conforms to XML.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] DTDs describe the structure of a class of documents via element and attribute-list declarations.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Element declarations name the allowable set of elements within the document, and specify whether and how declared elements and runs of character data may be contained within each element.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Attribute-list declarations name the allowable set of attributes for each declared element, including the type of each attribute value, if not an explicit set of valid values.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] DTD markup declarations declare which element types, attribute lists, entities, and notations are allowed in the structure of the corresponding class of XML documents.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] An element type declaration defines an element and its possible content.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] A valid XML document contains only elements that are defined in the DTD.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Element type declarations are ignored by *non-validating* SGML and XML parsers (in which cases, any elements are accepted in any order, and in any number of occurrences in the parsed document), but these declarations are still checked for form and validity.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] An attribute list specifies for a given element type the list of all possible attribute associated with that type.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] " with this type, without needing any declaration in the DTD, so the uniqueness constraint also applies to these defined identifiers when they are specified anywhere in a XML document.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] " pipe character) of notation names, where each notation name in the enumeration must also be declared in the document type declaration; this type is not supported in HTML parsers, but is valid in SGML and XML 1.0 or 1.1 (including XHTML and SVG).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] A default value can define whether an attribute must occur (`#REQUIRED`) or not (`#IMPLIED`), or whether it has a fixed value (`#FIXED`), or which value should be used as a default value ("…") in case the given attribute is left out in an XML tag.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Attribute list declarations are ignored by *non-validating* SGML and XML parsers (in which cases any attribute is accepted within all elements of the parsed document), but these declarations are still checked for well-formedness and validity.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The entity declaration assigns it a value that is retained throughout the document.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] A common use is to have a name more recognizable than a numeric character reference for an unfamiliar character.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Entities help to improve legibility of an XML text.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] In general, there are two types: internal and external.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Reference to the "author" internal entity is not substituted in the replacement text of the "signature" internal entity.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The "%" character for introducing parameter entity references in the DTD loses its special role outside the DTD and it becomes a literal character.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] However, the references to predefined character entities are substituted wherever they occur, without needing a validating parser (they are only introduced by the "&" character).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] They provide a complete reference to unparsed external entities whose interpretation is left to the application (which interprets them directly or retrieves the external entity themselves), by assigning them a simple name, which is usable in the body of the document.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] For example, notations may be used to reference non-XML data in an XML 1.1 document.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] This declares the Media Type of external images with this type, and associates it with a notation name "type-image-svg".
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The declared notation name must be unique within all the document type declaration, i.e. in the external subset as well as the internal subset, at least for conformance with XML.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Notations can be associated to unparsed external entities included in the body of the SGML or XML document.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The `PUBLIC` or `SYSTEM` parameter of these external entities specifies the FPI and/or the URI where the unparsed data of the external entity is located, and the additional `NDATA` parameter of these defined entities specifies the additional notation (i.e., effectively the MIME type here).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Notations may also be associated directly to elements as additional meta-data, without associating them to another external entity, by giving their names as possible values of some additional attributes (also declared in the DTD within the `<!ATTLIST ...>` declaration of the element).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The example above shows a notation named "type-image-svg" that references the standard public FPI and the system identifier (the standard URI) of an SVG 1.1 document, instead of specifying just a system identifier as in the first example (which was a relative URI interpreted locally as a MIME type).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] This annotation is referenced directly within the unparsed "type" attribute of the "img" element, but its content is not retrieved.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] It also declares another notation for a vendor-specific application, to annotate the "sgml" root element in the document.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] In both cases, the declared notation named is used directly in a declared "type" attribute, whose content is specified in the DTD with the "NOTATION" attribute type (this "type" attribute is declared for the "sgml" element, as well as for the "img" element).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] However, the "title" attribute of the "img" element specifies the internal entity "example1SVGTitle" whose declaration that does not define an annotation, so it is parsed by validating parsers and the entity replacement text is "Title of example1.svg".
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The effective content for the "img" element be the content of this second external resource.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Only one notation name may be specified in the value of ENTITY attributes (there is no support in SGML, XML 1.0 or XML 1.1 for multiple notation names in the same declared external ENTITY, so separate attributes are needed).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] However multiple external entities may be referenced (in a space-separated list of names) in attributes declared with type ENTITIES, and where each named external entity is also declared with its own notation).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Notations are also completely opaque for XML and SGML parsers, so they are not differentiated by the type of the external entity that they may reference (for these parsers they just have a unique name associated to a public identifier (an FPI) and/or a system identifier (a URI)).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Some applications (but not XML or SGML parsers themselves) also allow referencing notations indirectly by naming them in the `"URN:''name''"` value of a standard CDATA attribute, everywhere a URI can be specified.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] However this behaviour is application-specific, and requires that the application maintains a catalog of known URNs to resolve them into the notations that have been parsed in a standard SGML or XML parser.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] This use allows notations to be defined only in a DTD stored as an external entity and referenced only as the external subset of documents, and allows these documents to remain compatible with validating XML or SGML parsers that have no direct support for notations.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Even in validating SGML or XML 1.0 or XML 1.1 parsers, the external entities referenced by an FPI and/or URI in declared notations are not retrieved automatically by the parsers themselves.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The XML DTD syntax is one of several XML schema languages.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] However, many of the schema languages do not fully replace the XML DTD.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] Most XML schema languages are only replacements for element declarations and attribute list declarations, in such a way that it becomes possible to parse XML documents with *non-validating* XML parsers (if the only purpose of the external DTD subset was to define the schema).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] A *non-validating* parser may, however, elect not to read parsable *external entities* (including the *external subset*), and does not have to honor the content model restrictions defined in element declarations and in attribute list declarations.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] If the XML document depends on parsable external entities (including the specified *external subset*, or parsable external entities declared in the *internal subset*), it should assert `standalone="no"` in its XML declaration.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The validating DTD may be identified by using XML Catalogs to retrieve its specified *external subset*.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] If it just includes any PUBLIC identifier, it *may* be processed as standalone, if the XML processor knows this PUBLIC identifier in its local catalog from where it can retrieve an associated DTD entity.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] `person` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains one element named `name`, followed by one named `birthdate` (optional), then `gender` (also optional) and `socialsecuritynumber` (also optional).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The `?` indicates that an element is optional.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The reference to the `name` element name has no `?`, so a `person` element *must* contain a `name` element.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] `name` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains "parsed character data" (#PCDATA).
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] `birthdate` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains parsed character data.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] `gender` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains parsed character data.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] `socialsecuritynumber` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains parsed character data.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] An example of an XML file that uses and conforms to this DTD follows.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The DTD is referenced here as an external subset, via the SYSTEM specifier and a URI.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] One can render this in an XML-enabled browser (such as Internet Explorer or Mozilla Firefox) by pasting and saving the DTD component above to a text file named *example.dtd* and the XML file to a differently-named text file, and opening the XML file with the browser.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] The files should both be saved in the same directory.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] However, many browsers do not check that an XML document confirms to the rules in the DTD; they are only required to check that the DTD is syntactically correct.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] For security reasons, they may also choose not to read the external DTD.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] An XML DTD can be used to create a Denial-of-service attack by defining nested entities that expand exponentially, or by sending the XML parser to an external resource that never returns.
[src:xxe-prevention/document-type-definition] For this reason, .NET Framework provides a property that allows prohibiting or skipping DTD parsing, and recent versions of Microsoft Office applications (Microsoft Office 2010 and higher) refuse to open XML files that contain DTD declarations.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] The XML 1.0 standard defines the structure of an XML document.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] The standard defines a concept called an entity, which is a term that refers to multiple types of data unit.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] One of those types of entities is an external general/parameter parsed entity, often shortened to external entity, that can access local or remote content via a declared system identifier.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] The system identifier is assumed to be a URI that can be accessed by the XML processor when processing the entity.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] The XML processor then replaces occurrences of the named external entity with the contents that is referenced by the system identifier.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] If the system identifier contains tainted data and the XML processor dereferences this tainted data, the XML processor may disclose confidential information normally not accessible by the application.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] Similar attack vectors apply the usage of external DTDs, external style sheets, external schemas, etc. which, when included, allow similar external resource inclusion style attacks.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] Attacks can include disclosing local files, which may contain sensitive data such as passwords or private user data, using `file://` schemes or relative paths in the system identifier.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] Since the attack occurs relative to the application processing the XML document, an attacker may use this trusted application to pivot to other internal systems, possibly disclosing other internal content via HTTP requests or launching a SSRF attack to any unprotected internal services.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] In some situations, an XML processor library that is vulnerable to client-side memory corruption issues may be exploited by dereferencing a malicious URI, possibly allowing arbitrary code execution under the application account.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] Other attacks can access local resources that may not stop returning data, possibly impacting application availability if too many threads or processes are not released.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] The application does not need to explicitly return the response to the attacker for it to be vulnerable to information disclosures.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] An attacker can leverage DNS information to exfiltrate data through subdomain names to a DNS server under their control.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] The examples below are from OWASP's *Testing for XML Injection (WSTG-INPV-07)*.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] When the PHP "expect" module is loaded, remote code execution may be possible with a modified payload.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] Since the entire XML document is communicated from an untrusted client, it is not usually possible to selectively validate or escape tainted data within the system identifier in the DTD.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-attack] The XML processor could be configured to use a local static DTD and disallow any declared DTD included in the XML document.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] An *XML eXternal Entity injection* (XXE), which is now part of the OWASP Top 10 via the point **A4**, is attack against applications that parse XML input.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] This issue is referenced in the ID 611 in the Common Weakness Enumeration referential.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet will help you prevent this vulnerability.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] For more information on XXE, please visit XML External Entity (XXE).
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] Disabling DTDs also makes the parser secure against denial of services (DOS) attacks such as Billion Laughs.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] Per: According to this post, starting with libxml2 version 2.9, XXE has been disabled by default as committed by the following patch.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] Per this blog post, both Adobe ColdFusion and Lucee have built-in mechanisms to disable support for external XML entities.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] As of ColdFusion 2018 Update 14 and ColdFusion 2021 Update 4, all native ColdFusion functions that process XML have a XML parser argument that disables support for external XML entities.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] Since there is no global setting that disables external entities, developers must ensure that every XML function call uses the correct security options.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] Support for external XML entities is disabled by default as of Lucee 5.4.2.10 and Lucee 6.0.0.514.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] The`DocumentBuilderFactory,` `SAXParserFactory` and `DOM4J` `XML` parsers can be protected against XXE attacks with the same techniques.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] The JAXP `DocumentBuilderFactory` setFeature method allows a developer to control which implementation-specific XML processor features are enabled or disabled.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] These features can either be set on the factory or the underlying `XMLReader` setFeature method.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] For a syntax highlighted example code snippet using `SAXParserFactory`, look here.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] StAX parsers such as `XMLInputFactory` allow various properties and features to be set.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] The setting `xmlInputFactory.setProperty(XMLConstants.ACCESS_EXTERNAL_SCHEMA, "");` is not required, as XMLInputFactory is dependent on Validator to perform XML validation against Schemas.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] Check the Validator section for the specific configuration.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] If your code does not have all of these lines, you could be vulnerable to an XXE attack.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] Note that both the `createXMLStreamReader` and `unmarshal` methods have several overloads with various source types, so you need to pick the right one and do a possible conversion.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] There were other issues as well that were fixed later, so to fully address these issues, Spring recommends you upgrade to Spring Framework 3.2.8+ or 4.0.2+.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] For Spring OXM, this is referring to the use of org.springframework.oxm.jaxb.Jaxb2Marshaller.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] For SAXSource and StreamSource instances, Spring processed external entities by default thereby creating this vulnerability.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] So, per the Spring OXM CVE writeup, the above is now safe.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] But if you were to use a DOMSource or StAXSource instead, it would be up to you to configure those sources to be safe from XXE.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] For DoS attacks using a direct DTD (such as the Billion laughs attack), a separate testing application from Josh Grossman at Bounce Security has been created to verify that .NET >=4.5.2 is safe from these attacks.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] This parser is protected from external entities at .NET Framework version 4.5.2 and protected from Billion Laughs at version 4.5.2 or greater, but it is uncertain if this parser is protected from Billion Laughs before version 4.5.2.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] These parsers are vulnerable to external entity attacks and Billion Laughs at versions below version 4.5.2 but protected at versions equal or greater than 4.5.2.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] These parsers are not vulnerable to external entity attacks or Billion Laughs before or after version 4.5.2.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] Also, at or greater than versions ≥4.5.2, these libraries won't even process the in-line DTD by default.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] Even if you change the default to allow processing a DTD, if a DoS attempt is performed an exception will still be thrown as documented above.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] ASP.NET applications ≥ .NET 4.5.2 must also ensure setting the `<httpRuntime targetFramework="..." />` in their `Web.config` to ≥4.5.2 or risk being vulnerable regardless or the actual .NET version.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] Omitting this tag will also result in unsafe-by-default behavior.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] For the purpose of understanding the above table, the `.NET Framework Version` for an ASP.NET applications is either the .NET version the application was build with or the httpRuntime's `targetFramework` (Web.config), **whichever is lower**.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] This configuration tag should not be confused with a similar configuration tag: `<compilation targetFramework="..." />` or the assemblies / projects targetFramework, which are **not** sufficient for achieving secure-by-default behaviour as advertised in the above table.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] `XmlDocument` can become unsafe if you create your own nonnull `XmlResolver` with default or unsafe settings.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] If you need to enable DTD processing, instructions on how to do so safely are described in detail in the referenced MSDN article.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] `System.Xml.XmlNodeReader` objects are safe by default and will ignore DTDs even when constructed with an unsafe parser or wrapped in another unsafe parser.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] `System.Xml.XmlReader` objects are safe by default.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] They are set by default to have their ProhibitDtd property set to false in .NET Framework versions 4.0 and earlier, or their `DtdProcessing` property set to Prohibit in .NET versions 4.0 and later.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] Additionally, in .NET versions 4.5.2 and later, the `XmlReaderSettings` belonging to the `XmlReader` has its `XmlResolver` set to null by default, which provides an additional layer of safety.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] Therefore, `XmlReader` objects will only become unsafe in version 4.5.2 and up if both the `DtdProcessing` property is set to Parse and the `XmlReaderSetting`'s `XmlResolver` is set to a nonnull XmlResolver with default or unsafe settings.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml-external-entity-prevention-cheat-sheet] `System.Xml.XmlTextReader` is **unsafe** by default in .NET Framework versions prior to 4.5.2.
