[src:xxe-prevention/xml] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:xxe-prevention/xml] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
